    public static String lambo_allmodel_des[]={"The Lamborghini Veneno is a limited production high performance sports car manufactured by Italian automobile manufacturer Lamborghini. Based on the Lamborghini Aventador, the Veneno was developed to celebrate Lamborghini's 50th anniversary. It was introduced at the 2013 Geneva Motor Show. When introduced, it had a price of US$4,000,000.\nThe Veneno is a very rare model; indeed, it is among Lamborghinis rarest models. There are only 13 worldwide: three Veneno Coup were produced in the colors of the Italian flag (green, white and red); a gray one is currently on display at MUDETEC (the Museum of Lamborghini Technologies hosted in the production plant in SantAgata Bolognese), and nine Veneno Roadsters. Each one of these cars has been sold at a price of approximately three million euros before tax, and they were all sold out even before being unveiled."

            ,"The Lamborghini Reventn is a mid-engine limited production sports car that debuted at the 2007 Frankfurt Motor Show. The official press release stated that only 20 vehicles would be sold to the public, with one additional car (marked as 00/20) produced for the Lamborghini museum. Each car is stamped with its number in the sequence of 20 between the driver and passenger seats.The few-off, with only 20 units produced at the price of  1 million before taxes has an identity all its own and an aeronautic-inspired design. The sharp edges, precise lines and clean surfaces anticipate a few aesthetic solutions that are then taken to the extreme by the Aventador Coup, such as the shape of the headlamps, the layout of the optical units, and the shape of the nose with its large air intakes. The body is made entirely of carbon fiber and is fitted out with an active rear spoiler that moves into three different positions depending on the speed."

            ,"The Lamborghini Revuelto is a mid-engine plug-in hybrid sports car produced by the Italian automobile manufacturer Lamborghini. It was officially unveiled on March 29, 2023 as a successor to the Aventador. As of July 2023, the Revuelto has gone into full production, with the first units expected to be delivered in the last quarter of 2023.Just before the 60th anniversary of the marque, Lamborghini unveiled Revuelto, the first HPEV (High Performance Electrified Vehicle) hybrid super sports car. With the Revuelto, Lamborghini has established a new benchmark in performance, on-board technology, and driving pleasure. The ultimate thrill provided by the Revuelto is reached thanks to a powertrain that delivers 1015 CV total, combining the power of a brand-new 12-cylinder internal combustion engine with three high-density electric motors and a groundbreaking transversal dual clutch e-gearbox. The power of hybridization is harnessed to take performance and driving emotions to an unprecedented level."

            ,"The Lamborghini Countach LPI 800-4 is a limited-production mid-engine hybrid-electric sports car produced by the Italian automotive manufacturer Lamborghini and designed by its head of design Mitja Borkert. Unveiled on 14 August 2021, the car is inspired and named after the original Countach which was first introduced 50 years prior.Fifty years since its unveiling at the Geneva Motor Show, the legendary Lamborghini Countach is making headlines again with a limited-series hybrid supercar celebrating the visionary design that revolutionized modern sports cars forever and laid the foundations of the Lamborghini legacy. This is the new Countach LPI 800-4. Inspired by the past, made for the future."

            ,"The Lamborghini Huracn (Spanish for \"hurricane\";) is a sports car manufactured by Italian automotive manufacturer Lamborghini replacing the previous V10 offering, the Gallardo. The Huracn was revealed online in December 2013, making its worldwide debut at the 2014 Geneva Auto Show, and was released in the market in the second quarter of 2014.Sculptured and sensual, the Huracns design is based on the spiky hexagonal forms of the carbon atom, while the seamless roof profile is an unmistakable mark of the Lamborghini DNA. The Huracn is unique even in the dark, thanks to the alluringly technological light of its full-LED lighting system. Choose your favourite Lamborghini Huracn and discover its technical specifications."

            ,"The Lamborghini Sin FKP 37 is a limited production mid-engine hybrid sports car produced by the Italian automotive manufacturer Lamborghini. Unveiled online on 3 September 2019, the Sin is the first hybrid production vehicle produced by the company.Production of the Sin FKP 37 was limited to 63 units for the coupe and 19 for the roadster and all have already been sold. Lamborghini's Ad Personam division will be responsible for the manufacture of the Sin. The car was officially unveiled to the public at the 2019 Frankfurt Motor Show configured in a unique \"electric gold\" paint. It was also renamed to be known as the Sin FKP 37 honouring late Volkswagen Group chairman Ferdinand Karl Pich. \"FKP\" are the initials of his name and \"37\" are the last two numbers of his birth year (i.e. 1937).The power for the electric motor is stored in a supercapacitor unit instead of conventional lithium-ion batteries. The supercapacitor unit is integrated with the electric motor into the gearbox for a better weight distribution. A supercapacitor was chosen as it provides three times the power of a conventional lithium-ion battery of the same weight. The unit installed in the car is an evolution of the Aventador's starter motor and can store ten times more power than the unit it is based on. A regenerative braking system helps generate enough energy to recharge the supercapacitors. The electric motor counters the effect of deceleration and provides a power boost to the driver at speeds up to 130 km/h (81 mph). The motor supports low-speed manoeuvres such as parking and reversing."

            ,"The Lamborghini Urus is a luxury SUV manufactured by Italian automobile manufacturer Lamborghini. It was introduced in December 2017 as a 2018 model year production vehicle. The Urus is the first Lamborghini SUV and five-door vehicle in the modern era (under the ownership of Volkswagen Group), and the second SUV in the brand's history after the LM002, which was produced between 1986 and 1993.Lamborghini Urus is the first Super Sport Utility Vehicle in the world, merging the soul of a super sports car with the practical functionality of an SUV. Powered by Lamborghinis 4.0-liter twin-turbo V8 engine, the Urus is all about a performance mindset that brings together fun-to-drive and astounding vehicle capabilities. The design, performance, driving dynamics and unbridled emotion flow effortlessly into this visionary realization of authentic Lamborghini DNA."

            ,"The Lamborghini Aventador is a mid-engine sportscar produced by the Italian automotive manufacturer Lamborghini. In keeping with Lamborghini tradition, the Aventador is named after a Spanish fighting bull that fought in Zaragoza, Aragn in 1993. The Aventador is the successor for the Lamborghini Murcielago and is made by hand in Sant'Agata Bolognese, Italy.\nDESIGNED TO PUSH BEYOND PERFORMANCE\n" +
            "Revolutionary thinking is at the heart of every idea from Automobili Lamborghini. Whether it is aerospace-inspired design or technologies applied to the naturally aspirated V12 engine or carbon-fiber structure, going beyond accepted limits is part of our philosophy. The Aventador advances every concept of performance, immediately establishing itself as the benchmark for the super sports car sector. Giving a glimpse of the future today, it comes from a family of supercars already considered legendary."

            ,"The Lamborghini Aventador is a mid-engine sportscar produced by the Italian automotive manufacturer Lamborghini. In keeping with Lamborghini tradition, the Aventador is named after a Spanish fighting bull that fought in Zaragoza, Aragn in 1993. The Aventador is the successor for the Lamborghini Murcielago and is made by hand in Sant'Agata Bolognese, Italy. Lamborghini created the Aventador SVJ to embrace challenges head-on, combining cutting-edge technology with extraordinary design, while always refusing to compromise. In a future driven by technology, its easy to lose the genuine thrill of driving. But in the future shaped by Lamborghini, this wont be left behind, because there will always be a driver behind the wheel."

            ,"The Lamborghini Gallardo is a sports car built by the Italian automotive manufacturer Lamborghini from 2003 to 2013. It is Lamborghini's second car released under parent company Audi, and the best-selling model at the time with 14,022 built throughout its production run.The design of the Lamborghini Gallardo is also an icon in and of itself. The design project began in 2000, resulting in the unique combination of formal Lamborghini attributes into an individual unit. The strong aeronautics influence the designers drew inspiration from gave birth to a car that became legendary for its compact athleticism.The path toward the Gallardo officially began in 1998, when the idea of installing a 10-cylinder engine was revisited to create something never seen before in a Lamborghini car. The engine installed on the first Gallardo was a 5-liter, 10-cylinder V90 DOHC with four valves that delivered an output of 500 HP for a state-of-the-art creation. \n" +
            "The extraordinary vehicle could also boast a 6-speed gearbox equipped with latest-generation double- and triple-cone synchronizers and an all-aluminum structural chassis."

            ,"The Lamborghini Murcilago, produced by the Italian automaker Lamborghini from 2001 to 2010, served as the successor to the Diablo and held the position of the flagship V12 model in the company's lineup. Initially introduced as a coup in 2001, the Murcilago made its debut in North America for the 2002 model year. Notably, this car marked Lamborghini's first new design in over a decade and represented the brand's inaugural model under the ownership of German parent company Audi, a subsidiary of Volkswagen.\n" +
            "\n" +
            "Designed by Luc Donckerwolke, Lamborghini's head of design from 1998 to 2005, the Murcilago underwent several variations during its production. In 2003, a roadster variant was introduced, followed by the more powerful and updated LP 640 coup and roadster. Additionally, a limited edition LP 6504 Roadster was released. The final iteration to bear the Murcilago nameplate was the LP 6704 SuperVeloce, featuring the largest and last evolution of the original Lamborghini V12 engine.\n" +
            "\n" +
            "Production of the Murcilago concluded on November 5, 2010, with a total of 4,099 cars manufactured. Its successor, the Aventador, was unveiled at the 2011 Geneva Motor Show. Lamborghini's tradition of naming cars after Spanish Fighting Bulls continued with the Murcilago, named after a notable bull that survived a significant fight in Crdoba in 1879. \"Murcilago\" is Spanish for bat, and while the pronunciation in most of Spain is [mujelao], Lamborghini often uses the Southern Spanish and Latin American Spanish pronunciation, [musjelao], with an [s] sound."

            ,"The Lamborghini Diablo is a high-performance mid-engine sports car built by Italian automobile manufacturer Lamborghini between 1990 and 2001. It is the first production Lamborghini capable of attaining a top speed in excess of 320 kilometres per hour (200 mph). After the end of its production run in 2001, the Diablo was replaced by the Lamborghini Murcilago. The name Diablo means \"devil\" in Spanish.\n\n" +
            "The design of the Lamborghini Diablo was entrusted to Marcello Gandini, the same designer responsible for its two predecessors. However, when Chrysler Corporation acquired Lamborghini in 1987 and provided funding for the completion of the car's development, there was a notable shift in design direction. Chrysler's management was dissatisfied with Gandini's original designs, prompting them to task their design team in Detroit with a comprehensive redesign.\n" +
            "\n" +
            "This third redesign aimed to smooth out the sharp edges and corners characteristic of Gandini's initial design, resulting in a more streamlined appearance. Marcello Gandini, however, was notably unimpressed with the alterations to his original vision. Disappointed with the \"softened\" shape, he eventually realized his original design in the Cizeta-Moroder V16T.\n" +
            "\n" +
            "The car that emerged from this process was named the Diablo, continuing Lamborghini's tradition of naming its cars after breeds of fighting bulls. The Diablo specifically took its name from a fierce bull raised by the Duke of Veragua in the 19th century. This bull gained notoriety for engaging in a legendary battle with 'El Chicorro' in Madrid on July 11, 1869.\n" +
            "\n" +
            "The development of the Lamborghini Diablo is estimated to have incurred a total cost of 6 billion Italian Lire."

            ,"The Lamborghini Countach is a rear mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive sports car produced by the Italian automobile manufacturer Lamborghini from 1974 until 1990. It is one of the many exotic designs developed by Italian design house Bertone, which pioneered and popularized the sharply angled \"Italian Wedge\" shape. The style was introduced to the public in 1970 as the Lancia Stratos Zero concept car. The development of the Countach was initiated by Ferruccio Lamborghini with the goal of creating a successor to the Miura. The Miura was widely acclaimed after its introduction in 1966, but by 1970 new competitors including the Ferrari Daytona had been introduced to the market, and the Miura was showing its age. Chief engineer Paolo Stanzani and his staff began work on the Miura successor in 1970 under the project name \"LP112.\" From the beginning of the project, Stanzani's collaborators included test driver Bob Wallace, assistant engineer Massimo Parenti and designer Marcello Gandini of Bertone."

            ,"The Lamborghini Miura, a legendary sports car, was manufactured by the Italian automaker Lamborghini from 1966 to 1973. Notably, the Miura was the pioneering supercar to feature a rear mid-engined two-seat layout, a design that would later become the standard for high-performance sports and supercars. While the concept of such a layout was initially introduced in the production road car Ren Bonnet's Matra Djet in 1964, the Miura was the first to truly embody this configuration.\n" +
            "\n" +
            "Contrary to the preferences of company founder Ferruccio Lamborghini, who favored powerful and sophisticated grand touring cars, the Miura was conceived by Lamborghini's engineering team in their spare time. This marked a departure from the race car-derived machines produced by their local rival, Ferrari.\n" +
            "\n" +
            "The initial presentation of the Miura's rolling chassis took place at the 1965 Turin Auto Show, and the prototype P400 made its debut at the 1966 Geneva Motor Show. Impressively, the car garnered widespread acclaim from both show attendees and automotive journalists. Marcello Gandini's sleek styling and the groundbreaking mid-engine design were particularly noteworthy.\n" +
            "\n" +
            "As Lamborghini's flagship model, the Miura underwent periodic updates and remained in production until 1973. Following its discontinuation, the Countach joined the company's lineup in 1974, a year marked by challenging financial circumstances for Lamborghini. The Miura's legacy endures as one of the most iconic and influential sports cars in automotive history."

            ,"The first car produced by Lamborghini was the Lamborghini 350 GT. Introduced in 1964, the Lamborghini 350 GT marked the beginning of Lamborghini's venture into the high-performance sports car market. It was the company's inaugural production model and set the stage for Lamborghini's future success in the automotive industry.\n" +
            "\n" +
            "Designed by Touring of Milan, the Lamborghini 350 GT featured a classic and elegant design, with a 3.5-liter V12 engine producing around 280 horsepower. The car was presented at the Geneva Motor Show in 1964, showcasing Lamborghini's commitment to creating powerful and luxurious vehicles that could compete with established brands like Ferrari."};

    public static String lambo_allmodel_spec[]={"The engine is a development of the Aventador's 6.5-litre V12 and generates a power output of 750 PS (552 kW; 740 hp) at 8,400 rpm and 690 Nm (509 lbft) of torque at 5,500 rpm. The increase in power was achieved by enlarging the air intakes and modifying the exhaust system.The vented engine cover improves cooling to the engine, while the extreme aerodynamic elements present on the car signify its track-focused characteristics. It has a top speed of 356 km/h (221 mph) and has a 097 km/h (060 mph) acceleration time of 2.9 seconds. The car has a braking distance of 30 m (98.0 ft) from 970 km/h (600 mph), and can produce 1.41 G while cornering."

            ,"A road vehicle with extreme characteristics, the Reventn is also a limited-edition work of art. A masterpiece of design with only 20 units built, inspired by the latest trends in aeronautics.\n" +
            "The 12 cylinder engine that powers the Reventn Roadster is one of the most powerful aspirated engines in the world: from 0 to 100 km/h in just 3.4 seconds, reaching a top speed of 330 km/h."

            ,"The Lamborghini Revuelto showcases an impressive combination of power and advanced technology. Under its hood, the supercar boasts a newly developed 6.5-liter V12 engine, accompanied by three electric motors strategically placed for optimal performance, resulting in a remarkable combined power output of 746.5 kW. The engine is naturally aspirated with a displacement of 6498.5 cm3, delivering a robust performance with 825 PS (814 horsepower) for the internal combustion engine (ICE) and an additional 190 PS (187 horsepower) from the electric motors. The combined force reaches an extraordinary 1,015 PS (1,001 horsepower). Torque figures are equally impressive, with the ICE generating 725 Nm, the electric motors contributing 82 Nm, and the combined torque peaking at 807 Nm. The power is efficiently managed through an 8-speed dual-clutch automated manual transmission, driving all four wheels with an all-wheel-drive system.\n" +
            "\n" +
            "In terms of performance, the Lamborghini Revuelto achieves an exhilarating top speed exceeding 350 km/h (217 mph). Acceleration is equally striking, with a 0100 km/h (062 mph) time of just 2.5 seconds and a rapid 0200 km/h (0124 mph) acceleration in under 7.0 seconds. The supercar maintains a dynamic yet manageable profile with a dry weight of 1,772 kg (3,907 lb), supported by state-of-the-art carbon-ceramic brake discs measuring 41038 mm with 10-piston calipers at the front and 39032 mm discs with 4-piston calipers at the rear. The Revuelto incorporates a lithium-ion battery with a rated capacity of 3.8 kWh, contributing to an electric range of 10 km (6.2 mi) based on the WLTP standard. In essence, the Lamborghini Revuelto represents a technological marvel, seamlessly blending internal combustion power with electrified performance to deliver an extraordinary driving experience."

            ,"The heart of the Countach LPI 800-4 is a longitudinally positioned (LP) naturally-aspirated 6.5-liter V12 engine, generating an impressive 574 kW (780 PS; 770 hp). Additionally, a 48-volt electric motor, integrated within the 7-speed automated manual transmission, contributes an extra 25 kW (34 PS; 34 hp). The powertrain is designed to be efficient, incorporating a regenerative braking system that channels energy into a supercapacitor instead of a traditional lithium-ion battery, resulting in a lighter overall weight.\n" +
            "\n" +
            "With a dry weight of 1,595 kg (3,516 lb) and a front-to-rear weight distribution of 43-57, the Countach LPI 800-4 achieves a remarkable balance. Lamborghini asserts impressive performance figures, stating that the car can accelerate from 0100 km/h (062 mph) in just 2.8 seconds, reach 0200 km/h (0124 mph) in 8.6 seconds, and attain a top speed of 355 km/h (221 mph). This underscores the Countach LPI 800-4 as a powerful and agile supercar, blending cutting-edge technology with Lamborghini's iconic design and performance heritage."

            ,"The Huracn maintains the 5.2-litre naturally aspirated Audi/Lamborghini V10 engine with an additional 0.2 litres, compared to the Gallardo, tuned to generate a maximum power output of 449 kW (602 hp; 610 PS). To ensure its balance and performance, the car is mid-engined. The engine has both direct fuel injection and multi-point fuel injection. It combines the benefits of both of these systems; it is the first time this combination is used in a V10 engine. To increase its efficiency, the Huracn's engine also includes a start-stop system.[citation needed] The firing order of the engine is 1, 6, 5, 10, 2, 7, 3, 8, 4, 9. This is printed on a metal plate on the top of the engine, as with all other Lamborghini models.With a curb weight of 1,553 kg (3,424 lb), the Huracn LP 610-4 has a power-to-weight ratio of 2.55 kg (5.62 lb) per horsepower."

            ,"Based on the Lamborghini Aventador, the Sin FKP 37 shares its engine with the SVJ variant of the Aventador, but an electric motor integrated into the gearbox adds another 25 kW (34 PS; 34 hp) to the power output. Other modifications to the engine include the addition of titanium intake valves, a reconfigured ECU and a new exhaust system raising the power output to 576 kW (784 PS; 773 hp). The total power output is 602 kW (818 PS; 807 hp), making the Sin the most powerful production Lamborghini.The improvements made to the car help accelerate it from 0 to 100 km/h (62 mph) in 2.8 seconds and attain an electronically limited top speed of 355 km/h (221 mph) but the official top speed is to be confirmed."

            ,"The Urus accelerates from 0 to 62 mph (100 km/h) in 3.6 seconds and reaches a top speed of 190 mph (306 km/h). The EPA fuel economy is rated at 14 mpgUS (16.8 L/100 km; 16.8 mpgimp) combined (city and highway), 12 mpgUS (19.6 L/100 km; 14.4 mpgimp) city, and 17 mpgUS (13.8 L/100 km; 20.4 mpgimp) highway. The engine is rated at a maximum power output of 478 kW (641 hp; 650 PS) at 6,000 rpm and maximum torque of 850 Nm (627 lbft) at 2,2504,500 rpm. The engine has been heavily reworked for the Urus, and is uprated by 100 PS (74 kW; 99 hp) and 80 Nm (59 lbfft) of torque more than the Cayenne Turbo, with changes such as new cylinder heads.a top speed of 305 km/h (190 mph) making it one of the world's fastest production SUVs. The Urus can accelerate from 0100 km/h (62 mph) in 3.6 seconds and 0200 km/h (124 mph) in 12.8 seconds."

            ,"The Lamborghini Aventador LP 7004 is propelled by Lamborghini's formidable 6,498 cc (6.5 L; 396.5 cu in) 60 V12 engine, internally designated as the L539. This engine, a significant achievement as Lamborghini's fifth in-house design and only the second V12 since the 350GT's 3.5-liter powerplant, exemplifies the brand's commitment to high-performance engineering.\n" +
            "\n" +
            "Key specifications of the Aventador's powertrain include:\n" +
            "\n" +
            "Displacement: 6,498 cc (396.5 cu in)\n" +
            "Maximum Power: 700 PS (515 kW; 690 hp) at 8,250 rpm\n" +
            "Minimum Power-to-Weight Ratio: 378 PS (278 kW; 373 bhp) per tonne\n" +
            "Maximum Torque: 690 Nm (509 lbft) at 5,500 rpm\n" +
            "Firing Order: 1, 12, 4, 9, 2, 11, 6, 7, 3, 10, 5, 8\n" +
            "CO2 Emissions: 398 g/km (23 oz/mi)\n" +
            "Combined Fuel Consumption: 17.2 L/100 km (16.4 mpgimp; 13.7 mpgUS)"

            ,"The Lamborghini Aventador SVJ boasts an awe-inspiring 6.5-liter V12 engine that propels the supercar with 770 PS (759 hp) and 720 Nm of torque, enabling blistering acceleration from 0 to 100 km/h in an astounding 2.8 seconds and achieving a top speed of over 350 km/h. Its aerodynamics are finely tuned with an active ALA 2.0 system, featuring a dynamic rear wing for optimal downforce. The lightweight carbon fiber monocoque chassis, paired with the all-wheel-drive system and advanced suspension, ensures unparalleled agility. The car rolls on 20-inch front and 21-inch rear wheels, wrapped in Pirelli P-Zero Corsa tires. Carbon-ceramic brakes, measuring 400 mm in the front and 380 mm in the rear, provide robust stopping power. With a dry weight of 1,525 kg and a weight distribution of 43% front and 57% rear, the Aventador SVJ delivers a perfect blend of power, precision, and performance, setting a new standard for the ultimate driving experience."

            ,"The Lamborghini Gallardo, a remarkable sports car produced from 2003 to 2013, boasts a powerful 5.2-liter V10 engine, generating a range of 500 to 570 horsepower, with acceleration times of 0 to 60 mph in approximately 3 to 4 seconds. Equipped with a 6-speed manual transmission or an optional automated manual transmission, it achieves a top speed of around 200 mph (322 km/h). With an all-wheel-drive system providing exceptional traction, the Gallardo is a two-seater, mid-engine coupe or convertible, weighing between 3,100 to 3,400 pounds (1,400 to 1,500 kg). Its dimensions reflect a compact and low-slung design, featuring independent suspension with double wishbones for both the front and rear, contributing to its impressive performance and iconic status in the realm of high-performance sports cars."

            ,"The Lamborghini Murcilago, produced by the Italian automaker Lamborghini from 2001 to 2010, is a legendary supercar known for its striking design and high-performance capabilities. It is powered by a formidable mid-mounted 6.2-liter V12 engine, delivering an impressive output ranging from around 572 to 661 horsepower depending on the specific model and iteration. The Murcilago is typically equipped with a 6-speed manual transmission or an optional automated manual transmission, allowing it to accelerate from 0 to 60 mph in approximately 3.0 to 3.8 seconds, with a top speed exceeding 200 mph (322 km/h). Featuring the iconic scissor doors, the Murcilago is a two-seater, all-wheel-drive coupe, showcasing Lamborghini's commitment to a distinctive and aggressive design philosophy. The car's weight is around 3,800 to 4,000 pounds (1,700 to 1,800 kg), and its dimensions contribute to its aerodynamic and sleek profile. The Murcilago's combination of raw power, bold aesthetics, and exhilarating performance solidifies its status as a true icon in the realm of high-performance sports cars."

            ,"The Lamborghini Diablo, produced from 1990 to 2001, was equipped with a mid-mounted 5.7 to 6.0-liter V12 engine, producing power outputs ranging from approximately 485 to 595 horsepower. The car, available with a 5-speed manual or a 5-speed automated manual transmission, could accelerate from 0 to 60 mph in around 3.5 to 4.5 seconds, and it boasted a top speed of over 200 mph (322 km/h). The Diablo, with its distinctive scissor doors and aggressive design, weighed approximately 3,300 to 3,900 pounds (1,500 to 1,800 kg), making it a powerful and iconic supercar in the automotive world."

            ," the Countach was equipped with a mid-mounted 4.0-liter V12 engine, producing around 375 horsepower. It featured a striking and futuristic design that set new standards for exotic cars. The Countach of this time was known for its scissor doors, sharp angular lines, and a low-slung profile. It was typically paired with a 5-speed manual transmission. Acceleration from 0 to 60 mph took approximately 5.6 seconds, and the top speed was around 186 mph (299 km/h). Keep in mind that specifications might vary slightly depending on the specific model and any modifications made to individual vehicles. The Lamborghini Countach from 1974 remains a legendary and influential car in the history of high-performance automobiles."

            ,"The Lamborghini Miura, produced from 1966 to 1973, is widely regarded as one of the most iconic and groundbreaking sports cars in automotive history. It was named after the famous Spanish fighting bull breeder, and its mid-engine design set new standards for high-performance vehicles. The Miura was powered by a transversely mounted 3.9-liter V12 engine, producing around 350 horsepower. The car featured a 5-speed manual transmission and was capable of accelerating from 0 to 60 mph in approximately 6 seconds, with a top speed of about 170 mph (273 km/h). The Miura's sleek and aerodynamic design, crafted by Marcello Gandini at Bertone, was revolutionary for its time and influenced the design of many subsequent sports cars. With its distinctive looks and impressive performance, the Lamborghini Miura remains a classic and highly sought-after collector's car."

            ,"The Lamborghini 350 GT, launched in 1964, boasted a 3.5-liter V12 engine generating an impressive 280 horsepower. Mated to a 5-speed manual transmission, it offered dynamic performance with a 0 to 60 mph acceleration in about 6.8 seconds. The car's capabilities extended to a top speed of approximately 158 mph, showcasing the remarkable power and speed that marked Lamborghini's entrance into the world of high-performance sports cars during its early years."};

